</p>
<h3><span id="Scaling_X.2C_Y.2C_Z"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Scaling_X,_Y,_Z">Scaling X, Y, Z</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Color_balance&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Scaling X, Y, Z">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>If the image may be transformed into <a href="/wiki/CIE_1931_color_space" title="CIE 1931 color space">CIE XYZ tristimulus values</a>, the color balancing may be performed there.  This has been termed a “wrong von Kries” transformation.<sup id="cite_ref-Terstiege1972_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Terstiege1972-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Fairchild1998_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fairchild1998-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Although it has been demonstrated to offer usually poorer results than balancing in monitor RGB, it is mentioned here as a bridge to other things. Mathematically, one computes:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle \left[{\begin{array}{c}X\\Y\\Z\end{array}}\right]=\left[{\begin{array}{ccc}X_{w}/X'_{w}&amp;0&amp;0\\0&amp;Y_{w}/Y'_{w}&amp;0\\0&amp;0&amp;Z_{w}/Z'_{w}\end{array}}\right]\left[{\begin{array}{c}X'\\Y'\\Z'\end{array}}\right]}">
